[[span class="capt blue"]] [[image https://scp-wiki.wdfiles.com/local--files/paradise-lot/wikitan.png link="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Wikipe-tan_face.svg"]] [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portal:Anime_and_manga|Anime and manga portal]]][[/span]][[span class="lazy"]]spacer[[/span]]
[[/div]]
[[div class="bigbody"]]
//**Paradise Lot**// ([[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_language|Japanese]]]: パラダイス・ロット, [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hepburn_romanization|Hepburn]]]: //Paradaisu Rotto//; stylized as //**paradise lot**//) is a Japanese [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Science_fiction_on_television|science-fiction]]] [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tech_noir|tech noir]]] [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anime|anime]]] television series created by [# Takahashi Masaki] for and animated by [# FUTURA] that ran from 1992 to 1996. The series is set in the year 1999 and follows [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyborg|cyborg]]] private contractor Ekaterina Lot and her spaceship //Paradise// as she completes bounties at the behest of the Foundation Safety Protectorate, a shady organization dedicated to studying and classifying [# mysterious phenomena] in the universe colloquially called ‘anomalies’. Lot is joined later in the series by various different characters such as Japanese-American conman Honjo Masamune, advanced combat [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gynoid|gynoid]]] Raakel, twin [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extrasensory_perception|esper]]] teenagers Sara and Michael, and others (though usually not more than two at once).

The series is known for its use of applied [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Retrofuturism|retrofuturism]]], intentionally juxtaposing futuristic technology such as interplanetary travel, recreational spaceships, and armed [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Powered_exoskeleton|exosuits]]] with then current or slightly outdated technology such as floppy disks, phone booths, and record players. The synthesizer-based soundtrack composed by [# Himiko Niigata] also received positive acclaim. Several home releases and remasters have been available since 2001.
[[/div]]
[[toc]]
+ Plot
[[size 110%]]@@    @@//See also: [# List of Paradise Lot characters]//[[/size]]
[[div class="bigbody"]]
The series occurs in early 1999, decades after humanity has mastered recreational space travel and gone through widespread [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Space_colonization|colonization]]] efforts in order to move off of a resource-depleted and overpopulated Earth. One of the many agencies involved in expanding their intergalactic influence is the Foundation Safety Protectorate (FSP), whose main operation is the containment and research of anomalous occurrences. To achieve this, they employ a system where they reward [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bounty_(reward)|bounties]]] through contacts to private contractors - or 'agents' - who are able to deliver a specific anomaly to a FSP drop point within a week from their assignment.

[# Ekaterina Lot], one of the most infamous FSP agents, owns and lives on a recreational [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Starship#Fictional_types|starship]]] named the //Paradise//; the series follows her as she hops from cities to planets in order to complete contracts. Her contact is an anonymous male by the name of [# K] (though he implies it's an [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudonym#Concealing_identity|assigned nickname]]]). Anomalies contracted for retrieval usually vary from objects to humanoids and are often already in use by other parties, prompting Lot to solve additional problems during her expeditions. She often runs into trouble with [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interstellar_travel|intersolar]]] authorities as most of the collection types for anomalies are flimsily [[[https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/extralegal|extralegal]]] or closely related to terrorist groups and belligerents. Lot also enlists the help of civilians related to the contract by giving them a cut of the profits - the first example in the series being [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mecha|mech]]] police pilot [# Aurelion Comparri] - and occasionally even recruits them onto the //Paradise//.
[[/div]]
+ Setting and themes
[[div class="bigbody"]]
Episodes usually occur in [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Villain_of_the_week|villain-of-the-week]]] formats, with later seasons involving several multi-episode story arcs. Heavy visual focus on neon/colored lighting, firearm realism, and multilingual text became hallmarks of the show. The series also focuses on the blurred line between sufficiently advanced technology and the [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paranormal|paranormal]]] or unknown. Other recurring themes include [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Predeterminism|predeterminism]]], [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Absurdism|absurdism]]], [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corporatocracy|corporatocracy]]], and [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Political_corruption|political corruption]]]. 

The setting was largely inspired by [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyberpunk|cyberpunk]]] works by authors such as [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Gibson|William Gibson]]], [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philip_K._Dick|Philip K. Dick]]], [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Katsuhiro_Otomo|Katsuhiro Otomo]]], and [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Masamune_Shirow|Masamune Shirou]]]; it also makes direct references to [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blade_Runner|Blade Runner]]] and [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Akira_(1988_film)|Akira]]]. Several episodes in the series were intentionally done as homages to different genres and shows. The most notable of those episodes upon initial release was "Cop by Cop by Killer", a tribute to famous detective drama series //[[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taiyō_ni_Hoero!|Taiyō ni Hoero!]]]//. Despite the harsh setting of the series, Lot is characterized as a happy and charismatic yet strong-willed and capable character; most of the recurring characters are characterized similarly.
[[/div]]
+ Production
[[div class="bigbody"]]
[[include :scp-wiki:component:image-block-base name=https://scp-wiki.wdfiles.com/local--files/paradise-lot/masaki-small.png|caption=Takahashi Masaki in 1993.|width=200px|link="https://scp-wiki.wdfiles.com/local--files/paradise-lot/masaki-small.png"|align=left]]
Preproduction started when FUTURA approached Masaki to create a [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Television_film|TV movie]]] adaptation of his manga series [# Force Unit: Gaelstar]. Although he denied initially, citing creative burnout on the manga, Masaki offered to make an original concept that the studio could retain. Then in-house FUTURA writer Nakato Ryoichi assisted Masaki in creating the basis for what would become the first pilot of the series.

Masaki and Ryoichi both felt a mecha anime would be inappropriate given the genre’s saturation and the popularity of the recent [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mobile_Suit_Gundam:_Char's_Counterattack|Gundam]]] [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mobile_Suit_Gundam_F91|movies]]] at the time. They eventually decided on an episodic, exploration-based show to allow the studio and future writers more leeway in subsequent productions. The addition of a female protagonist was at Ryoichi’s request, who thought a female lead would make the series appeal to more viewers. He noted in an expo interview that, “there were strong females before [in anime], but always secondary or subservient to the male leads… I wanted a woman who could stand on her own, someone boys and girls alike could admire.” Masaki later stated, “when he came to me and said ‘I want it to be a woman’, I was completely against it. He ignored me and instead talked at length about his vision and the character. I quickly became just as enamored as he was. It was the right decision.”

The series’s name is an intentional pun on the [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Milton|John Milton]]] epic poem [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paradise_Lost|Paradise Lost]]]; the names of both Lot and the //Paradise// are derived from the title. Lot’s appearance is heavily inspired by [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Heavy_Metal_L-Gaim_characters#Gaw_Ha_Leccee|Gaw Ha Leccee]]], a character from [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heavy_Metal_L-Gaim|Heavy Metal L-Gaim]]] that Masaki was fond of. Himiko Niigata joined the production team as a favor for Masaki, though she expressed great enthusiasm after viewing the pilot’s rough storyboards and even created an [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Image_song|image album]]] to help conceptualize the final pilot. The team wanted to have a realistic depiction of firearms, leading to Ryoichi asking his friend [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenichi_Sonoda|Kenichi Sonoda]]] (of burgeoning fame due to [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bubblegum_Crisis|Bubblegum Crisis]]] and [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gunsmith_Cats|Gunsmith Cats]]]) for assistance. Sonoda chose the [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smith_&_Wesson_459|S&W M459]]] pistol that Lot carries as well as most of the on-screen firearms in the series and provided the team with hand-drawn design documents for them.

The pilot - simply called //Paradise Lot// - debuted as a TV movie special on September 12th, 1992. Even though FUTURA had planned to eventually create a series, overwhelming positive ratings led the studio to release the first episode of the series (second numerically) only two weeks later. In [[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rerun|syndications]]], the pilot movie was recut and titled as the series's first episode “Requiem for an Angel’s Child”.
